Inverse-designed metamaterial waveguides can be classified into two categories: analog and digital62,67–69. To design a device, the design region is first specified and then discretized into M × N unit shapes, called “pixels”. The “pattern” is thus considered as a matrix of the pixels with permittivity distribution of [ε]M×N, where each pixel (i, j) has a permittivity of εi,j accordingly. Then, algorithms are employed to find an optimized permittivity distribution to fulfill figure-of-merit (FOM). As exemplified in the upper panel in Fig. 10a, analog metamaterial waveguides generally have relatively small pixels366–368≪λ/10\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\left( { \ll\!\! \lambda {{{\mathrm{/}}}}10} \right)$$\end{document} to meet the perturbation theory369. Thus, the permittivity εi,j or its shape information can vary continuously to calculate the gradients information of the FOM (discretization is conducted later to produce binary devices)15. In contrast, pixel dimensions of a digital metamaterial waveguide are much larger (~λ/10) (lower panel in Fig. 10a)68,370, and the permittivity εi,j is restricted to binary distribution, e.g. corresponding to the logical “1” or “0” state.Fig. 10Inverse-design tutorials for meta-waveguides.
